In this case, the definition is:

```
        "prop_security_EpssVulnAssessmentRelationship_security_probability": {
                    "anyOf": [
                        {
                            "type": "number"
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "string",
                            "pattern": "^-?[0-9]+(\\.[0-9]*)?$"
                        }
                    ]
        },
```

Yes, this can be populated with text string decimals: https://spdx.github.io/spdx-spec/v3.0.1/model/Security/Classes/EpssVulnAssessmentRelationship/

```
{
  "type": "EpssVulnAssessmentRelationship",
  "spdxId": "urn:spdx.dev:epss-CVE-2020-28498",
  "relationshipType": "hasAssessmentFor",
  "security_probability": "0.00105",
  "security_percentile": "0.42356",
  "from": "urn:spdx.dev:vuln-cve-2020-28498",
  "to": ["urn:product-acme-application-1.3"],
  "suppliedBy": ["urn:spdx.dev:agent-jane-doe"],
  "publishedTime": "2023-10-05T00:00:30Z"
}
```

Exponents are not allowed by the regexp. On second thought, the mapping of json `number` to `int / float` is a mistake and can be removed. The difficulty with float vs string remains.

